Package: HausdorffGoF
Type: Package
Title: Computing Test Statistics and P-Values of the Hausdorff Goodness-of-Fit Test
Version: 0.2.0
Authors@R: c(
    person("Dimitrina S.", "Dimitrova",
           email = "D.Dimitrova@city.ac.uk",
           role  = "aut"),
    person("Yun",          "Jia",
           email = "yunjia2019@gmail.com",
           role  = c("aut", "cre")),
    person("Vladimir K.",  "Kaishev",
           email = "Vladimir.Kaishev.1@city.ac.uk",
           role  = "aut"))
Description: Computes the Hausdorff (H) test statistic and its p-value for one-sample and two-sample goodness-of-fit testing. The H statistic measures the Hausdorff distance between empirical and theoretical (one-sample) or two empirical (two-sample) cumulative distribution function curves under the Chebyshev metric, and equals geometrically the side length of the largest square (hypercube) inscribable between the two curves. Exact one-sample p-values are computed via a rectangle-probability representation  using the Exact-KS-FFT method of Dimitrova, Kaishev and Tan (2020). Two-sample p-values are obtained by exact or Monte Carlo permutation. Univariate algorithms
    run in O(m+n) time; a bivariate implementation is also included.
